Tetra Argent Consists of Amorthland, Modek, Tinollia, and Tagal. Amorthland Who rules? Amorthland is part of Tetra Argent. The ruler is King of the Tetra Argent, Alfrick IV of Dinmire. Why is it called that? “Tetra” refers to the 4 continents under the Realm of the King: Amorthland, Modek, Tinollia, and Tagal. Argent (aka silver) refers to the state religion, The Grey Gods. Amorthland is named after Amorth the Conqueror, who led a great migration of his people through this land some 400 years ago. Motto “Might, Harmony, Argent.” Symbol Four 3-pointed stars, all silver, sometimes stylized on top of a pale or yellow scroll, otherwise on a black background. Political Structure Monarchy with Republic/representative elements.  Strong central government with various support programs in place, mostly consisting of military power. Highly effective and structured military recruitment and training regime, so military loyalty is strong (especially for how spread out it is). It is sometimes possible for wealthy merchants to work their way into a title or Nobility, especially if they marry strategically. Customs Most cities and towns celebrate Harvest season with an extravagant city-wide party. Values Conservative/Liberal: Leans Conservative Individualistic & Collectivist: Both. People value their autonomy and dislike being told

what to do, but know they serve others for a greater purpose than themselves (some of this is due to the influence of the Grey). Power Distance: Medium. Uncertainty Avoidance: Medium. Orientation to Time: High. Highly human-populated, and humans are very aware of their own mortality, as they have short lives. Gender Egalitarianism: Low.         Assertiveness: High. Doing vs. Being Orientation: High Doing. Humane Orientation: Medium. Indulgence vs. Restraint: Leans Restraint. Superstitions/View on magic People use magic for daily life on the small scale if they are able. Fashion European analog. Conflicts Things have been uneasy for roughly the past 50 years between Argent and Ulkken, as Alfrick III attempted to invade Ulkken in order to “bring it into the fold”. Ulkken resisted the invasion. Residents of Niputu also resisted Alfrick III’s invasion, and are their own country. Argent tends to deny this, and has occasionally made invasion attempts. However, Alfrick IV is not as strong of a military leader as his father, and hasn’t been successful in ruling Niputu. Trade Major exports: Beer, Wheat, Hops, Cattle, Soldiers, Clerics Basic History When the King’s father Alfrick III was young, he led a military force across Amorthland, Modek, Tinollia, and Tagal to “Unite the Tetra” under one kingdom. He mostly succeeded. It has been 51 years since then.         In the places furthest from Amorthland’s capital city, Dinmire, there is less structure and governmental support. If there is no military support in any given area, cities rule themselves and often consider themselves independent from Argent. Primary Humanoid Inhabitants Humans, Dwarves, Half-Elves, Elves Notable Wildlife Dragons in the Northeast Vampire bats are known to live in the Southern Mountain area Mountain lions all along mountain range Religions The Petty (75%), The Sun (17%), Grey Gods (4%) Languages Common, Dwarvish, Mordigok, Orc, Elvish, Tagalan  Modek Who rules?         Modek is part of Tetra Argent. The ruler is King of the Tetra Argent, Alfrick IV of Dinmire. Why is it called that? More than 500 years ago the people in this area migrated from an island called Mordee. The name shifted and transitioned with time, but the people have mostly kept their traditions. Motto         “Might, Harmony, Argent.”  (Previously “Keep the Traditions” or “A Talana i na Fuʻuna” in Mordigok) Symbol         Four 3-pointed stars, all silver, sometimes stylized on top of a pale or yellow scroll, otherwise on a black background.         Previously (and still sometimes used) Blue ship on a white sea. Political Structure         Previously a widespread but locally effective government was in place. Modek was

more fractured, with the states self-regulating much of the time.         Now, the governmental structure of Tetra Argent is being imposed. Some are glad for the military support, but many are upset at the change. Some Modekians have been promoted as noble powers, and a handful of nobles from Amorthland have been installed as “temporary” command. Customs By their calendar, it is year 718. Values Individualistic & Collectivist: Individualistic, except on Naval matters. Power Distance: Low. Modekians do not care that much status. They more care that things are done, and done well. Uncertainty Avoidance: Low. They are a seafaring culture, they must expect the unexpected. Orientation to Time: Medium Gender Egalitarianism:High. Women can sail just as well as men. Assertiveness: Medium. They will speak their minds, but not cause deliberate offense. Doing vs. Being Orientation: Doing Humane Orientation: Medium Indulgence vs. Restraint: Indulgence Superstitions/View on magic Fashion Large area. Seafaring, South American analog. Many European analog influences. Tinollia is part of Tetra Argent. The ruler is King of the Tetra Argent, King Dwendal. Why is it called that? Motto Symbol Political Structure Customs By their calendar, it is year 718. Values Conservative/Liberal: Liberal. Individualistic & Collectivist: Individualistic. There are too many different types of people for them to think collectively. Power Distance: Medium Uncertainty Avoidance: Low. This is a land of change. “Prepare for change, or be changed” is a common saying. Orientation to Time: Medium Gender Egalitarianism: Low. It doesn’t matter who you were born as, it matters who you are now. Assertiveness: High. In a land of uncertainty and change, one must take the actions they think are appropriate. Doing vs. Being Orientation: Leans Doing, but also has “acceptance” cultural expectations. Humane Orientation: Medium Indulgence vs. Restraint: Indulgence. You live one time, might as well enjoy it. Superstitions/View on magic Fashion All over the place. Lots of Middle Eastern analog and African analog influences. Liberal and colorful. It’s hot in the main populated areas. Who rules? Lestef the Bold rules, who was the son of Honora the Wise, who was the daughter of Lorentaf the Blue. Why is it called that?         Scholars aren’t sure, though they suspect it has to do with what Dwarves in this area called themselves in many years past. Motto         “Broken Ice, Unbroken Water” or in Dwarvish- “Gahtistyk Fristan, Ontuig Vannsk” It is a reminder to not let the cold north break one’s spirit as it breaks ice, and that the people should be as united and unflappable as water. Ice is surface level. Ice is temporary, and it melts into water. Symbol A green fist and arm holding a black hammer, on a white background. Political Structure Sovereign State Parliamentary Monarchy. The Monarchy has sway over much of the political power, especially the military, but the Parliament holds most of the power and control. Customs By their calendar, it

Motto “Past, Present, Fate.” Symbol A stylized white fox on a dark red background. Political Structure         Strict Monarchy. Power is spread among a wide number of Nobility. Hundreds of years of feuds and disagreements make the government seem fractured and weakened from the outside, but if threatened, factions in Segashi would unite quickly against a common enemy.         Military is an extensive royal guard, and several standing-armies or mercenary groups, the most famous of which is the Queen’s Crimson Hand.  Customs Common, Batinese, and Sylvan are taught to children in schools, but only Elvish is spoken among adults, and especially the nobility. Speaking other

languages is frowned upon. Most elves here are want for nothing- their long lives have given them time to gather all necessary resources to make a comfortable life, and make sure their own kind have everything they need as well. By their calendar, it is year 564. Travel is encouraged, but the implied purpose of this is so that one can see how the rest of the world is screwed up, and therefore appreciate the culture of Segashi more fully. The parable goes that when a road forks into two, there is always another way to travel besides the 2 roads (you can go back the way you came, or leave the trail entirely, thereby creating “The Third Path”). Some take this as an optimist world view (“Don’t give up! There is always the Third Path.”), and some take this as avoiding extremes (“Left or right, both are rigid choices. Giant Squids seen all around Protomain Giant Sea Turtles and Dragon Turtles seen near Tagal and Sunomich   Culture Map of the world with country names I have a lot of notes on the different cultures of the world that you don’t need to read!   If you have an idea of the type of place your character would come from, I will give you a few options to pick from (or maybe create a culture based on what you want!). You will learn about your character’s culture at that point.  Humanoid Species (a.k.a Playable Races) In order of population.  Human  The most prevalent humanoid species on the planet. They come in all types- pale to dark, short to tall, skinny to fat. Humans are the most adaptable and ambitious people among the common races. Whatever drives them, humans are the innovators, the achievers, and the pioneers of the worlds.  Half-Elf Half-elves are from many different parts of the world. They combine what some say are the best qualities of their elf and human parents. It is easy to tell a Half-Elf from a Human or an Elf-- they are not as rough as the former, but not as fair as the latter. They typically live to 190-250 years old.  Elf Elves are a magical people of incredible grace, living in the world much longer than the rougher humanoid species. They typically live to 350-400 years old.  Dwarf The short and stout humanoid species. Very prevalent in some parts of the world, they tend to find homes and stay there. Bold and hardy, dwarves are known as skilled warriors, miners, and workers of stone and metal. They live to about 300 years of age, but never much longer than that.  Orc Referred to as “Half-Orc” in D&D rules text. On Ardos, Orcs are quite humanoid, and they should be thought of as the same as “Half-Orc”. Orcs’ grayish pigmentation, sloping foreheads, jutting jaws, prominent teeth, and towering builds make them plain to see. What they lack in stealth, they make up in brute force.  Orcs cannot breed with humans, but they can breed with Elves, making the Gith. They rarely live longer than 75 years.  Half-Dwarf Half-Dwarves are often mistaken for one or the other, but they have traits of both. Just as humans and elves can produce offspring, so too can humans and dwarves. They blend in well, so it is difficult to tell their total population. They live to about 180 years of age.  Tiefling Created in an unknown pact or curse in many ages past, Tiefling are humans

with demon blood in their veins. To be greeted with stares and whispers, to suffer violence and insult on the street, to see mistrust in every eye: this is the lot of the tiefling.  There are not many tieflings in any one area, but they are found where humans or elves dwell. You might find a few in a medium-sized city, but not more than that. As their number is small and they cannot mate with other species, they will sometimes mate when they can, most often conceiving children out of wedlock or during their travels.  They are marked by horns, a fleshy tail, grey/purple/red toned skin, and a demonic visage- eyes of all one color. Temperamentally and physically, they are like humans in every other way (including age).  Gith / Elf-Orc A species considered an abomination by many, the Gith are half Elf and half Orc. Tall and thin, they lack the grace of an elf and the brute strength of an orc. They are unmistakable, as they take on the most obvious traits of both their parents.  They are rare, and you might only see them in areas that border both Elf and Orc populations.  They live to about 100-120 years old.  Halfling The diminutive halflings survive in a world full of larger creatures by avoiding notice or, barring that, avoiding offense.  Often known as “the outdated” or “the extinct”, Halflings as a species are known to be in steady decline for at least the last 250 years or so. The Halfling language is still very prevalent in some parts of the world.  If you see one, it will be only among a handful that you see in your life.  They live to about 150 years old.  Genasi  Humans or elves born of magic. From where? It depends on the Genasi. How? The magic of a djinn. By some they are considered blessed, and by others cursed. They carry the power of the elements in their blood. Sometimes they are mistaken as Human or Elf, but sometimes they stick out depending on their skin tone or magical abilities. If you see one, it will be only among a handful that you see in your life.  They typically live a bit longer than humans (even the elf genasi), up to 120-140 years old. Physically, they are exactly like their non-magical counterparts in every other way. If they have a child, the child will only have small or lingering magical traits that the parent had.  Fallen Aasimar Aasimar are celestial and angelic beings that serve as guardians to the planes of the gods. A Fallen Aasimar is a celestial that has been struck down from the heavens, stripped of much of their power and all of their memories from their time as an angel.  When they access certain parts of their remaining celestial magic, two skeletal, ghostly, flightless wings will appear on their back as a

reminder of their heavenly crimes.  They can blend in as elves, as they have fair features and pointed ears. Their eyes are all one color, and typically their hair and skin are shades of black, grey, silver, gold, or white. You may only see one in your entire life, if you travel often.  They live 400-500 years after they have fallen.  Other Notes About Species Species have evolved over time, just like the species on Earth. There is a genealogical trail-- Humans, Elves, and Dwarves share a common ancestor. Orcs are more closely related to Elves than Humans, and Halflings are more closely related to Dwarves than Humans.  Each species below can only mate with the one next to it: Orcs - Elves - Humans - Dwarves - Halflings Orcs and Elves make Gith. Dwarves and Halflings make Gnomes. Tieflings can only mate with Tieflings.  Magically altered species: Tieflings, Dragonborn, Genasi, Angels/Aasimar. These all came to be by different methods than evolution by natural selection.  Diseases/Body Changes Vampires Vampirism is a curable disease. Humans, Elves, and Dwarves can contract Vampirism via contact with the saliva of a Vampire. If a being’s Vampirism remains uncured for a number of days, the being will die and become a Vampire. Vampires can only mate with Vampires of the same race, and when they do, produce sterile Vampire offspring. Vampires are a form of undead, and becoming one will change a being’s body. They do not appear in mirrors. Their canine teeth will get slightly longer, and sharp. Their bodies become cold and hardened, though quickened and more resilient. Their eyes take on a reddish hue. They thirst for blood.  Shifters Shifters are any humanoid race whose spirit has melded with a spirit of a bear, wolf, or large cat. A magic rift would draw the two spirits (living or dead) toward the same point, and where they meet, the magic rift forces their souls into one. This creates a being who is Shifted- forced into their animal spirit during any full moon. If a Shifter were particularly in-touch with their animal selves, they may be able to control the shifting. But that is yet to be seen.   Languages Below are a list of languages and their real-world equivalents. The equivalents are rough, and just meant to provide cultural context. Nobles that do actually work (or more prestigious jobs) will do 5 days on, 3 days off. Months: 13 full months (31 days each), and 2 short months (13 days and 8 days).
